issue.title: Retrieve dual variables of a qp problem solved via osqp
issue.body:
### Discussed in https://github.com/casadi/casadi/discussions/3426
Originally posted by **MarcFacerias** October 24, 2023 Hello, When trying to retrieve dual variables using opti.dual() syntaxis I only get Nans, I assume that's due to the feature not being implemented for conic solvers , do you know how could I retrieve those values from the osqp solution object? Thanks a lot, Marc

comment.body: Oh thanks, I'll rewrite my problem using the conic interface then

comment.body:
It works in the conic interface. Looks like retrieving the dual variables for conic problems are not implemented in the opti interface.

https://github.com/casadi/casadi/blob/ece7fced6edf5283df5c79c7dcb831c853ddb44c/casadi/core/optistack_internal.cpp#L937

issue.title: peculiar NLP sensitivity analysis cases
issue.body:
Don't get why this fails:

```python
from casadi import *

x = MX.sym("x")
p = MX.sym("p")

y = MX.sym("y")

solver = nlpsol("solver","sqpmethod",{"x":vertcat(x,y),"p":p,"f":(x-p)**2,"g":vertcat(y-x)})

print(solver(p=0,lbg=0,ubg=0))

f = Function("J",[p],[jacobian(solver(p=p,lbg=0,ubg=0)["x"],p)])

print(f(0))
```


This occurs naturally in the last gap-closing constraint of a multiple-shooting code with an objective depending only on a subset of states.

issue.title: peculiar NLP sensitivity analysis cases
issue.body:
Don't get why this fails:

```python
from casadi import *

x = MX.sym("x")
p = MX.sym("p")

y = MX.sym("y")

solver = nlpsol("solver","sqpmethod",{"x":vertcat(x,y),"p":p,"f":(x-p)**2,"g":vertcat(y-x)})

print(solver(p=0,lbg=0,ubg=0))

f = Function("J",[p],[jacobian(solver(p=p,lbg=0,ubg=0)["x"],p)])
```

comment.body:
Hi

I also tried to use sensitivities to "transform" an equality-constrained problem into an unconstrained one, because although its Jacobian is sparse, its Hessian isn't, yielding an enormous overhead in the coloring step (see #3424).

I encountered the same problems as reported below, but made one additional observation: I basically run the following:
```
constraints = @(x1,x2) ...
x0_inner = ...
x0_outer = ...
x_inner = casadi.MX.sym('x_inner', length(x0_inner), 1);
x_outer = casadi.MX.sym('x_outer', length(x0_outer), 1);

nlp_inner = struct('x', x_inner, 'p', x_outer, 'g', constraints(x_inner, x_outer));
S_inner = casadi.nlpsol('S_inner', 'sqpmethod', nlp_inner);
output_inner = S_inner('x0', x0_inner, 'p', x_outer, 'lbg', 0, 'ubg', 0);
output_inner_jac = casadi.Function('output_inner_jac',{x_outer},{jacobian(output_inner.x, x_outer)});
output_inner_jac(x0_outer)
```
Running this *once* will give me a Jacobian; running the final statement, i.e., `output_inner_jac(x0_outer)`, *again* will result in an error:
```
Error using casadi.Function/call
Error in Function::call for 'output_inner_jac' [MXFunction] at .../casadi/core/function.cpp:330:
.../casadi/core/function_internal.hpp:1616: Evaluation failed
```
For any other solver that I tried instead of sqpmethod (in particular KNITRO and IPOPT), it will fail *immediately*. 

Maybe this gives a direction for locating the problem, @jaeandersson?

issue.title: 'which_depends' not defined for External when using codegen with bonmin
issue.body:
Creating an nlpsol solver with bonmin and compiled code raises an error (passes with ipopt). 

Below is a minimal working example on linux using GCC. (however this happens on windows as well)
Removing the "discrete" option to nlpsol has no impact.

```
from casadi import * 
import subprocess

J = 0
w = SX.sym('w', 3)
g = w**2
discrete = [True, False, False]

# Create an NLP solver
nlp_prob = {'f': J, 'x': w, 'g': g}
nlp_solver = nlpsol('nlp_solver', 'bonmin', nlp_prob, {"discrete": discrete});
#nlp_solver = nlpsol('nlp_solver', 'ipopt', nlp_prob); # Solve relaxed problem

############################## try to codegen the solver #############################
source_path  = 'lv.c'
dest_path = 'lv.so'
nlp_solver.generate_dependencies(source_path)
cmd = f'gcc -fPIC -shared -O3 {source_path} -o {dest_path}'
subp = subprocess.Popen(cmd, stdout=subprocess.PIPE, shell=True)
print('Compiling solver...')
subp.wait()

############################## try to codegen the solver #############################
solver = nlpsol('solver','bonmin',dest_path,{"discrete": discrete})   # raises  .../casadi/core/function_internal.cpp:3501: 'which_depends' not defined for External
#solver = nlpsol('solver','ipopt',dest_path)                          # passes

```

this is the traceback:
```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "/home/thomas/Shared/GitHub/vehicle_3d/examples/misc.py", line 25, in <module>
    solver = nlpsol('solver','bonmin',dest_path,{"discrete": discrete})   # raises  .../casadi/core/function_internal.cpp:3501: 'which_depends' not defined for External
  File "/home/thomas/.local/lib/python3.10/site-packages/casadi/casadi.py", line 28956, in nlpsol
    return _casadi.nlpsol(*args)
RuntimeError: .../casadi/core/function_internal.cpp:145: Error calling BonminInterface::init for 'solver':
Error in Function::which_depends for 'nlp' [External] at .../casadi/core/function.cpp:1769:
.../casadi/core/function_internal.cpp:3558: 'which_depends' not defined for External
```

issue.title: Cmeel-based publishing
issue.body:
I am developing a c++ library with python bindings based on repositories such as [pinocchio](https://github.com/stack-of-tasks/pinocchio) and casadi itself.

I have found it very convenient to use wheel distributions based on [cmeel](https://cmeel.readthedocs.io/en/latest/) because it makes the whole process of dependencies installation easy with PIP wheels.

Will it be possible to create alternative cmeel-based wheel for casadi as [cmeel-cppad](https://github.com/cmake-wheel/cmeel-cppad) ? Probably, the question relates not the development, rather the permission to do so.

comment.body: You are for sure allowed to distribute casadi in alternative ways, but I don't have any bandwidth to look into this myself on unpaid time.
